  "prompt": "The club has 37 members, 20 of whom are women and 17 of whom are men. The club needs to form a 4 person party-planning committee. How many committees are possible if the committee must have 2 women and 2 men?",
  "response": "To determine the number of possible committees that can be formed with exactly 2 women and 2 men from the club, we need to use combinations.\n\nFirst, we calculate the number of ways to choose 2 women out of the 20 women:\n\\[ \\binom{20}{2} = \\frac{20!}{2!(20-2)!} = \\frac{20 \\times 19}{2 \\times 1} = 190 \\]\n\nNext, we calculate the number of ways to choose 2 men out of the 17 men:\n\\[ \\binom{17}{2} = \\frac{17!}{2!(17-2)!} = \\frac{17 \\times 16}{2 \\times 1} = 136 \\]\n\nNow, we multiply the number of ways to choose the women with the number of ways to choose the men to get the total number of possible committees:\n\\[ \\binom{20}{2} \\times \\binom{17}{2} = 190 \\times 136 = 25840 \\]\n\nTherefore, the number of possible committees consisting of 2 women and 2 men is \\( 25,840 \\).",
